data.title: The Editorial Team
data.text:
Jai BednallHead of Growth

Jai has been with News Corp since 2005. Originally a sports journalist, he covered all the local teams in his hometown of Adelaide before moving to Sydney in 2014. He helped grow news.com.au’s sports audience to the largest in the country while attending events like the Olympics, World Cup and even McGregor-Mayweather. In 2021, he transitioned to an audience role and now helps more readers discover news.com.au’s content as our Head of Audience.

Sad fallout of beloved Aussie duo

The Woodies were one of the best sporting tandems Australia produced, but their on-court magic hasn’t resulted in a lifelong friendship.

10-year-old’s ripped torso is terrifying

This Japanese youngster has been moulding his body and perfecting his moves to become a carbon copy of film legend Bruce Lee.

Wrist slap for AFL star’s ‘cheap shot’

The AFL has announced Richmond star Tom Lynch has been hit with a wet lettuce leaf after getting off his “cheap shot” with impunity.

AFL great annihilates angry journo

Essendon legend Tim Watson has dubbed Damian Barrett the “Voice of Treason” after the footy journalist attacked him yesterday.

Heartbreak after star’s $310m blunder

The richest game in world sport was decided by a star’s awful mistake as Fulham beat Brentford for a place in the Premier League.

Rafa Nadal slams ‘barbaric’ tennis move

This year’s US Open is officially an asterisk tournament after defending champion Rafael Nadal withdrew and hit out at organisers.

ESPN apologises for kneeling joke

A popular radio host admitted a gag about the only player in the NBA not to kneel during the anthem badly injuring his knee wasn’t funny.

Eddie McGuire mourns tragic death

The Collingwood president and TV personality’s rough week in the headlines has been put in perspective after his mother, Bridie, died.

‘The AFL have slaughtered their brand’

The AFL has come under fire for standing down one of its own journalists for tweeting an Instagram post by a Richmond star’s wife.

America angered by Barty’s Open snub

Aussie tennis champ Ash Barty’s decision to skip this year’s US Open because of COVID-19 fears has not been well received abroad.
